ryday life.A substantial introduction defines Visual Culture as well as providing an historic overview of the origins of current academic and feminist practice. The volume is divided into three sections: Fine Art, Design and Mass Media. Each section begins with a contextualising Introduction and then discusses the visual media specific to that area, incorporating wider issues such as class, culture and ethnicity. A range of methods and analyses are adopted including questionnaire sampling, in-depth case studies, historiographical overview of theoretical material as well as writing about current practices.Feminist Visual Culture is a topical and comprehensive overview of this field providing both introductory access to the key debates and a more specialist understanding of their relevance within a specific medium.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aGender Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh1 aArnold, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuckley, Cheryl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarson, Fiona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaplin, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHole, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJefferies, Junis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnight, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLloyd, Fran, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNiblock, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPajaczkowska, Claire, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1